<styl>by <m2>By <m0>INA PAIVA CORDLE<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Business Writer<ql>
<m1><ep>
<m0> Miami ranks as the fifth least affordable place for executives to live, among 75 U.S. housing markets, an E&Y Kenneth Leventhal Real Estate Group report released Wednesday shows.<ep>
  Only San Francisco, Los Angeles, Honolulu and the Oakland/East Bay area are less affordable, according to the 1996 Study of Housing Costs. Fort Lauderdale also ranks near the bottom, at 57th out of 75.<ep>
  The report compares the cost of owning a four-bedroom home or renting a two-bedroom luxury apartment (--) with amenities such as a pool and patio or access to recreational facilities like a golf course (--) in relation to the local median household income.<ep>
  It's geared to show how attractive a city is for companies considering moving corporate headquarters there, said Jim Miller, managing partner for E&Y Kenneth Leventhal's Miami Real Estate Group.<ep>
  Metropolitan Miami's ranking dropped to 71 this year from 63 last year. In 1996, an average household in Dade has to spend 35.5 percent of its income for housing. A Fort Lauderdale household must shell out 28.5 percent.<ep>
  By contrast, in Oklahoma City, which ranked most affordable, housing costs take up just 19.5 percent of household income.<ep>
  Other Florida cities ranked include Orlando, 43rd; West Palm Beach, 54th; Sara<m2><ql>
